<br>
Thats a great post with an example of someone willing to spend some of their &quot;playing time&quot; to help out another player. Thats where it gets troublesome for some folks. Some folks really treasure their time and don't want to be pestered while playing.<br>
<br>
Its not a matter of being mean or anything.. I kind of compare it to something like this... <br>
<br>
I'm trying to read a book during some downtime to relax and unwind. I can really get into a book sometimes and &quot;escape&quot; into the world the author(s) have created. But every 15 minutes my telephone rings and its another darned telephone soliciter asking me to buy something.<br>
<br>
Now in this example the solution is easy. Unplug the phone. But you can't do that in EQ. Thus people get annoyed about intrusions on their play time. Its like chatting in EQ for me. I dont mind getting tells from friends in EQ, but I don't really chat with folks. Mostly because I play a chanter (and sometimes another character in extreme circumstances) and I want to pay attention to whats going on. Especially with my snarer falling asleep at the keyboard all the time and our mobs running off to go get his friends! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Or it could be just logistics. A former guildmate of mine sent me a tell on the weekend asking me to enchat 3 bars of plat. &quot;Sure np!&quot; I tell him, &quot;but we just started our PoG raid and its probably gonna be 5 or 6 hours&quot;. Obviously I wasn't gonna port out of PoG just to chant his bars and then comeback. But anyways, I digress. <p>Kzan Verto<BR>
Giver of "da juice" (tm)
